{{EM software tool |name=PFT3DR |website=http://www.chem.byu.edu/node/807 |long description=PFT3DR is package for determining orientations and origins of imaged particles and computing a three-dimensional reconstruction from the images and their assigned orientations and origins. The programs are enhanced versions of the PFT algorithm developed by Baker and Cheng (2000) and the Fourier Bessel reconstruction algorithm of Crowther et al. (1970). The original adaptations of the PFT3DR programs were specific to icosahedral viruses, but were enhanced to support nearly all symmetries found in biological particles. Other enhancements are described on the PFT3DR web site. |version=2 |contact=David_Belnap at byu.edu |os support=Unix (Linux, Mac OS X, etc.), VMS |image support=same as Bsoft |cost=Free/Open Source |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Baker TS, Cheng RH |title=A model-based approach for determining orientations of biological macromolecules imaged by cryoelectron microscopy |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=116 |issue=1 |pages=120–30 |year=1996 |pmid=8742733 |doi=10.1006/jsbi.1996.0020 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Crowther RA, Amos LA, Finch JT, De Rosier DJ, Klug A |title=Three dimensional reconstructions of spherical viruses by fourier synthesis from electron micrographs |journal=Nature |volume=226 |issue=5244 |pages=421–5 |year=1970 |month=May |pmid=4314822 |doi= |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Fuller SD, Butcher SJ, Cheng RH, Baker TS |title=Three-dimensional reconstruction of icosahedral particles--the uncommon line |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=116 |issue=1 |pages=48–55 |year=1996 |pmid=8742722 |doi=10.1006/jsbi.1996.0009 |url=}} |ref4={{cite journal |author=Bubeck D, Filman DJ, Cheng N, Steven AC, Hogle JM, Belnap DM |title=The structure of the poliovirus 135S cell entry intermediate at 10-angstrom resolution reveals the location of an externalized polypeptide that binds to membranes |journal=J. Virol. |volume=79 |iss