{{EM software tool |name=EM3D |website=http://em3d.stanford.edu/index.html |long description=EM3D is a software application designed to analyze and visualize electron microscope (EM) tomography data. It is especially for cellular and molecular biologists. From a tilt series of 2D electron micrographs taken at many tilt angles with respect to the electron beam, this program can then perform auto-align and quickly render those data into a lucid 3D model, which allows you to perform object rotating for viewing. In addition, EM3D also provides analysis tools for quantify structural information from the models, including their moments, proximity relationships, and spatial reliability. And all of these functions can be executed with a very intuited graphic user interface. EM3D is available free-of-charge Mac OS X for PowerPC or Intel, and Windows. EM3D was developed in the laboratory of Dr. U. J. McMahan, Professor of Neurobiology and of Structural Biology at Stanford University School of Medicine and continues to be developed at the Dept. of Biology, Texas A&M University. |version=2.0 |contact=grantser@bio.tamu.edu |os support=Windows, Mac OS X for PowerPC or Intel |image support= |cost=Free for academic use |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Ress D, Harlow ML, Schwarz M, Marshall RM, McMahan UJ |title=Automatic acquisition of fiducial markers and alignment of images in tilt series for electron tomography |journal=J Electron Microsc (Tokyo) |volume=48 |issue=3 |pages=277–87 |year=1999 |pmid=10425746 |doi= |url= |postscript=''EM3D's scheme for the automatic alignment of tilt-images is described.''}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Ress DB, Harlow ML, Marshall RM, McMahan UJ |title=Methods for generating high-resolution structural models from electron microscope tomography data |journal=Structure |volume=12 |issue=10 |pages=1763–74 |year=2004 |month=October |pmid=15458626 |doi=10.1016/j.str.2004.07.022 |url= |postscript=''EM3D approach to model generation is detailed.''}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Harlow ML, Ress D, Stoschek A, Marshall RM, McMahan UJ |title=The architecture of active zone material at the frog's neuromuscular junction |journal=Nature |volume=409 |issue=6819 |pages=479–84 |year=2001 |month=January |pmid=11206537 |doi=10.1038/35054000 |url= |postscript=''EM3D is first used for exposing cellular architecture at macromolecular resolution.''}} |ref4={{cite journal |author=Petersen JD, Chen X, Vinade L, Dosemeci A, Lisman JE, Reese TS |title=Distribution of postsynaptic density (PSD)-95 and Ca2+/calmodulin-dependent protein kinase II at the PSD |journal=J. Neurosci. |volume=23 |issue=35 |pages=11270–8 |year=2003 |month=December |pmid=14657186 |doi= |url= |postscript=''EM3D is used to examine the architecture of the postsynaptic density at brain synapses.''}} |ref5={{cite book |author=Ress, D., Harlow, M.L., Marshall, R.A., and McMahan, U.J. |title=Proceedings of the 25th Annual International Conference of IEEE |year=2003 |pages=774-777 |chapter=Optimized Method for Isodensity Surface Models Obtained with Electron Microscope Tomography Data |isbn= |postscript=''EM3D's method for creating optimal isodensity surface models is described.''}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=IMOD |website=http://bio3d.colorado.edu/imod/ |long description=IMOD is a set of image processing, modeling and display programs used for tomographic reconstruction and for 3D reconstruction of EM serial sections and optical sections. The package contains tools for assembling and aligning data within multiple types and sizes of image stacks, viewing 3-D data from any orientation, and modeling and display of the image files. It includes a complete graphical user interface for generating tomograms, combining tomograms from tilt series taken around two axes, and stacking tomograms from serial sections. |version=4.1 |contact=mast at colorado dot edu |os support=Linux, Windows, Mac OS X |image support=MRC, TIFF |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:GNU General Public License|GPL]] |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Kremer JR, Mastronarde DN, McIntosh JR |title=Computer visualization of three-dimensional image data using IMOD |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=116 |issue=1 |pages=71–6 |year=1996 |pmid=8742726 |doi=10.1006/jsbi.1996.0013 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Mastronarde DN |title=Correction for non-perpendicularity of beam and tilt axis in tomographic reconstructions with the IMOD package |journal=J Microsc |volume=230 |issue=Pt 2 |pages=212–7 |year=2008 |month=May |pmid=18445149 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2818.2008.01977.x |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Mastronarde DN |title=Dual-axis tomography: an approach with alignment methods that preserve resolution |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=120 |issue=3 |pages=343–52 |year=1997 |month=December |pmid=9441937 |doi=10.1006/jsbi.1997.3919 |url=}} }}
