{{EM software tool |name=PyTom |website=http://www.biochem.mpg.de/en/rg/foerster/Content_Software/PyTom/index.html |long description=PyTom is a python-based package for tomogram analysis. It supports tasks such as particle localization and identification by template matching, subtomogram averaging, and subtomogram classification. The package is open source, does not rely on any commercial software, and is platform-independent. The implementation in python should allow easy scripting for specific tasks. |version=1.0.1 |contact=foerster@biochem.mpg.de, hrabe@biochem.mpg.de, ychen@biochem.mpg.de |os support=Linux, Mac OS, Windows |image support= .em, .spi, .mrc |cost=Free |license= GPL / BSD |program language=Python |ref1={{cite journal |author= Hrabe T, Chen Y, Pfeffer S, Cuellar LK, Mangold AV, Förster F|title= PyTom: a python-based toolbox for localization of macromolecules in cryo-electron tomograms and subtomogram analysis. |journal=J Struct Biology |volume=178|issue=2|pages= 178-88|year=2012 |pmid= |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2011.12.003| url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.jsb.2011.12.003|postscript=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author= Chen Y, Hrabe T, Pfeffer S, Pauly O, Mateus D, Navab N, Förster F|title=Detection and identification of macromolecular complexes in cryo-electron tomograms using support vector machines. |journal=Biomedical Imaging (ISBI), 2012 9th IEEE International Symposium on |volume=|issue=|pages=1373-76 |year=2012 |pmid= |doi=10.1109/ISBI.2012.6235823| url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1109/ISBI.2012.6235823|postscript=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=RAPTOR |website=http://www-vlsi.stanford.edu/TEM/software.htm |long description=Robust Alignment and Projection Estimation for Tomographic Reconstruction (RAPTOR) is a free available software to align raw stacks obtained from electron microscopes for tomographic purposes. It is intended to automatically obtain a full-precision alignment comparable to the one obtained with extended manual intervention. Fiducial particles are needed in the image for the alignment. It has been designed to be compatible with IMOD software, so results can be checked with the usual IMOD tools for alignment and reconstruction. |version=2.1 |contact=famat at stanford dot edu |os support=Linux |image support=MRC |cost=Free |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Amat F, Moussavi F, Comolli LR, Elidan G, Downing KH, Horowitz M |title=Markov random field based automatic image alignment for electron tomography |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=161 |issue=3 |pages=260–75 |year=2008 |month=March |pmid=17855124 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2007.07.007 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=SerialEM |website=http://bio3d.colorado.edu/SerialEM/ |long description=SerialEM is a program to acquire tilt series for electron tomography on Tecnai and newer JEOL microscopes. It uses an approach based on prediction of specimen position during the tilt series from the position at previous tilts. With this method, it achieves both the robustness of the older approach to tilt series acquisition (track and focus at every tilt) and the speed of the newer precalibration approach. It provides a complete interface for camera control and image acquisition, viewing, and saving. It includes a low dose mode for tracking and focusing away from the area of interest, energy filter control, acquisition of tilt series using a montage of overlapping frames, and a navigator module for mapping the grid and returning to selected locations. It supports Gatan, Tietz, FEI, AMT, and some Direct Electron CCD cameras. |version=2.8 |contact=mast at colorado dot edu |os support=Microsoft Windows |image support=MRC |cost=Free for academic use |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Mastronarde DN |title=Automated electron microscope tomography using robust prediction of specimen movements |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=152 |issue=1 |pages=36–51 |year=2005 |month=October |pmid=16182563 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2005.07.007 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=TOM Toolbox |website=http://www.biochem.mpg.de/tom/ |long description=The Tomography Toolbox is a collection of functions that extend the capability of the MATLAB (+ Image Procesing Toolbox) numeric computing environment. The toolbox supports a wide range of functions for tomography.
*Automated data acquisition procedures have changed the perspectives of electron tomography (ET) in a profound manner. Elaborate data acquisition schemes with autotuning functions minimize exposure of the specimen to the electron beam and sophisticated image analysis routines retrieve a maximum of information from noisy data sets. ‘TOM software toolbox’ integrates established algorithms and new concepts tailored to the special needs of low dose ET. It provides a user-friendly unified platform for all processing steps: acquisition, alignment, reconstruction, and analysis. Designed as a collection of computational procedures it is a complete software solution within a highly flexible framework. TOM represents a new way of working with the electron microscope and can serve as the basis for future high-throughput applications. |version= |contact=tom@biochem.mpg.de |os support=Linux, Microsoft Windows |image support=EM,MRC,Spider |cost=Free |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Nickell S, Förster F, Linaroudis A, ''et al.'' |title=TOM software toolbox: acquisition and analysis for electron tomography |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=149 |issue=3 |pages=227–34 |year=2005 |month=March |pmid=15721576 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2004.10.006 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=TomoJ |website=http://u759.curie.fr/en/download/softwares/TomoJ |long description=TomoJ is a Java plug-in for ImageJ to perform tomographic reconstruction using ART, SIRT and WBP algorithms. It includes free reference alignment procedures in addition to standard cross-correlation methods in a friendly user interface. |version=2.15 |contact=tomoj@curie.fr |os support=All, same as [[w:ImageJ|ImageJ]] program |image support= |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:CeCILL|CeCILL Licence]] |program language=Java |ref1={{cite journal |author=Messaoudii C, Boudier T, Sanchez Sorzano CO, Marco S |title=TomoJ: tomography software for three-dimensional reconstruction in transmission electron microscopy |journal=BMC Bioinformatics |volume=8 |issue= |pages=288 |year=2007 |pmid=17683598 |pmc=1976622 |doi=10.1186/1471-2105-8-288 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Sorzano CO, Messaoudi C, Eibauer M, ''et al.'' |title=Marker-free image registration of electron tomography tilt-series |journal=BMC Bioinformatics |volume=10 |issue= |pages=124 |year=2009 |pmid=19397789 |pmc=2694187 |doi=10.1186/1471-2105-10-124 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=TxBR |website=https://confluence.crbs.ucsd.edu/display/ncmir/TxBR |long description=Tomographic reconstruction from large-format electron microscope data requires special procedures to handle geometric distortions arising from electron optics as opposed to light-ray optics. In particular, electrons travel in curvilinear paths through the sample, and defocus and other aberrations can have significant effects. TxBR handles geometric nonlinearities associated with charged-particle optics, distortion due to sample warping, and transform sets associated with non-standard modes of data collection. In addition, TxBR makes provision for marker-free alignment and specialized montaging for tomography of serial sections. |version=3.0 |contact=sph at ncmir dot ucsd dot edu |os support=Linux, Windows (&ge; XP), Mac OS X (PowerPC and Intel) |image support=MRC |cost=Free |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite book |author=S. Phan, A. Lawrence |title=Congress on Image and Signal Processing, Vol. 2 |publisher= |year=2008 |pages=176-182 |chapter=Tomography of Large Format Electron Microscope Tilt Series: Image Alignment and Volume Reconstruction |isbn=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Lawrence A, Bouwer JC, Perkins G, Ellisman MH |title=Transform-based backprojection for volume reconstruction of large format electron microscope tilt series |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=154 |issue=2 |pages=144–67 |year=2006 |month=May |pmid=16542854 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2005.12.012 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=UCSF Tomography |website=http://www.msg.ucsf.edu/em/EMNEW2/tomography_page.html |long description=UCSF Tomography is an integrated software suite that provides full automation from target finding, sequential tomographic data collection, to real-time reconstruction for both single and dual axes as well as automated acquisition of random conical data sets. This software was implemented based upon a novel approach in which the compustage tilting is modeled as geometric rotation. The spatial movement of the sample as a result of stage tilting can be predicted based upon previously collected tomographic images. Therefore, there is no need to collect tracking and focusing images during the entire tomographic data collection. A significant dose saving can thus be achieved and is critical in collecting cryo tilt series. Real-time reconstruction is achieved by calculating a weighted back-projection on a small Linux cluster (five dual-processor computer nodes) concurrently with the UCSF tomography data collection running on the microscope’s computer, and using the fiducial-marker free alignment data generated during the data collection process. The real-time reconstructed 3D volume provides users with immediate feedback to fully asses all aspects of the experiment ranging from sample choice, ice thickness, experimental parameters to the quality of specimen preparation. To facilitate dual-axis tomographic data collection, a hierarchical scheme for target finding and relocation after specimen rotation was developed and integrated with the predictive data collection and real-time reconstruction, allowing full automation from target finding to data collection and to reconstruction of 3D volumes with little user intervention. An on-site scheme was developed for random conical data collection where tracking and focusing are performed at the same location as the final conical tilt images. Lower magnifications combined with short exposure are used to substantially reduce dose and to allow larger tilt steps. The system also includes a feature for montaging untilted images to ensure that all of the particles in the tilted image may be used in the reconstruction. |version=v7.7.4E4 |contact=agard@msg.ucsf.edu |os support=Windows 2000, XP |image support=MRC |cost=Free for academic use |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Zheng SQ, Keszthelyi B, Branlund E, ''et al.'' |title=UCSF tomography: an integrated software suite for real-time electron microscopic tomographic data collection, alignment, and reconstruction |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=138–47 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=16904341 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.06.005 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Zheng QS, Braunfeld MB, Sedat JW, Agard DA |title=An improved strategy for automated electron microscopic tomography |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=147 |issue=2 |pages=91–101 |year=2004 |month=August |pmid=15193638 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2004.02.005 |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Zheng SQ, Kollman JM, Braunfeld MB, Sedat JW, Agard DA |title=Automated acquisition of electron microscopic random conical tilt sets |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=148–55 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=17169745 |pmc=2556511 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.10.026 |url=}} |ref4={{cite journal |author=Zheng SQ, Matsuda A, Braunfeld MB, Sedat JW, Agard DA |title=Dual-axis target mapping and automated sequential acquisition of dual-axis EM tomographic data |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=168 |issue=2 |pages=323–31 |year=2009 |month=November |pmid=19545637 |pmc=2776717 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2009.06.010 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=FEI Xplore3D™ Tomography Suite |website=http://www.fei.com/LifeSciences/ |long description=Xplore3D provides a complete solution for 3D tomographic acquisition, reconstruction, and visualization into one integrated package. The advanced capabilities include batch acquisition, dual-axis tomography, low-dose imaging, STEM tomography, energy filtering, and hardware acceleration for reconstruction. Batch scheduling permits unattended overnight data acquisition from multiple grid positions. Accurate, interactive alignment routines can use cross-correlation (no markers needed), bead tracking, or general feature tracking. Advanced reconstruction techniques include weighted back-projection, ART, and SIRT. Xplore3D includes a post-alignment and reconstruction module, Inspect3D. |contact=robert dot snyder at fei dot com |os support=Windows XP, |image support=most image formats |cost=Price available upon request |license=Perpetual right-to-use license |ref1={{cite journal |author=R.H.M. Schoenmakers, R.A. Perquin, T.F. Fliervoet, W. Voorhout, H. Schirmacher |title=New software for high resolution, high throughput electron tomography |journal=Microscopy and Analysis |volume=19 |issue=4 |pages=5-6 |year=2005 |month=July}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Li Peng, Sergey Ryazantsev, Ren Sun, Z. Hong Zhou |title=Three-Dimensional Visualization of Gammaherpesvirus Life Cycle in Host Cells by Electron Tomography |journal=Structure |volume=18 |issue=1 |pages=47-58 |year=2010 |month=January |pmid=20152152 |doi=10.1016/j.str.2009.10.017 |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Linda F. van Driel, Jack A. Valentijn, Karine M. Valentijn, Roman I. Koning, Abraham J. Koster |title=Tools for correlative cryo-fluorescence microscopy and cryo-electron tomography applied to whole mitochondria in human endothelial cells |journal=European Journal of Cell Biology |volume=88 |issue=11 |pages=669-684 |year=2009 |month=November |pmid=19726102 |doi=10.1016/j.ejcb.2009.07.002 |url=}} |ref4={{cite journal |author=Laura van Niftrik, Willie J.C. Geerts, Elly G. van Donselaar, Bruno M. Humbel, Alevtyna Yakushevska, Arie J. Verkleij, Mike S.M. Jetten, Marc Strous |title=Combined structural and chemical analysis of the anammoxosome: A membrane-bounded intracytoplasmic compartment in anammox bacteria |journal=Journal of Structural Biology |volume=161 |issue=3 |pages=401-410 |year=2008 |month=March |pmid=17604181 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2007.05.005 |url=}} }}
== Subvolume averaging ==
{{EM software tool |name=Dynamo |website=http://www.dynamo-em.org |long description=Dynamo is a software package for subtomogram averaging of Cryo-EM data. It is intended to provide users with big flexibility when adding new algorithms into standard procedures and adapting them for different computing environments as desktops, multicore machines, (multi)GPUs or clusters of CPUs. |version=1.0.116 |contact=daniel.castano@unibas.ch |os support=Linux, Mac OS, Windows |image support= .em, .spi, .mrc |cost=Free for academic use |license= GPL / BSD |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author= Castaño-Díez D, Kudryashev M, Arheit M, Stahlberg H|title= Dynamo: A flexible, user-friendly development tool for subtomogram averaging of cryo-EM data in high-performance computing environments. |journal=J Struct Biology |volume=|issue=3|pages= |year=2012 |pmid= |doi= http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.jsb.2011.12.017|url= |postscript=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=Jsubtomo |website=http://www.opic.ox.ac.uk/jsubtomo |long description=Jsubtomo is an open source software package based on Bsoft for averaging of tomographic sub-volumes. It includes tools for locating sub-volumes in tomograms using constrained cross-correlation, missing wedge-weighted averaging and refinement. Initial estimate of particle orientation can be easily included to constrain refinement. Python scripts are available for parallel processing and iterative refinement. |version=1.2 |contact=juha at strubi dot ox dot ac dot uk |os support=Linux, Mac OS, Windows |image support= Most, including .map, .mrc, .em, .spi, .img, .pif |cost=Free |license= |program language=C |ref1={{cite journal |author= Huiskonen JT, Hepojoki J, Laurinmäki P, Vaheri A, Lankinen H, Butcher SJ, Grünewald K.|title= Electron cryotomography of Tula hantavirus suggests a unique assembly paradigm for enveloped viruses.|journal= J Virology |volume=84|issue=10|pages=4889-97|year=2010|pmid= |doi= 10.1128/JVI.00057-10|url= |postscript=}} }}
