== Particle Selection ==
{{EM software tool |name=DoG Picker |website=http://ami.scripps.edu/redmine/projects/ami/wiki/FindEM |long description=DoG Picker is a simple particle picker that picks particles that resemble a blob using the [[w:Difference of Gaussians|Difference of Gaussians]] algorithm. It is intergrated into the TiltPicker program (below), |version=0.2 |contact=appion@scripps.edu |os support=Unix |image support=MRC |cost=Free/Open source |license=[[w:Apache License|Apache License v2.0]] |program language=Python |ref1={{cite journal |author=Voss NR, Yoshioka CK, Radermacher M, Potter CS, Carragher B |title=DoG Picker and TiltPicker: software tools to facilitate particle selection in single particle electron microscopy |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=166 |issue=2 |pages=205–13 |year=2009 |month=May |pmid=19374019 |pmc=2768396 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2009.01.004 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=FindEM |website=http://code.google.com/p/appion/downloads/list |long description=The FindEM program is based on projection matching using local real-space correlation with a series of templates. Real-space algorithms are traditionally relatively slow, but a fast Fourier based implementation of the real-space local correlation function has been introduced which is approximately two orders of magnitude faster for the projection matching application. This algorithm is referred to as the “Fast Local Correlation Function” or FLCF. |version=2.0 |contact=appion@scripps.edu |os support=Unix |image support=MRC |cost=Free/Open source |ref1={{Cite journal|first1=A.M.|last1=Roseman| year=2004|title=FindEM—a fast, efficient program for automatic selection of particles from electron micrographs | journal=Journal of Structural Biology|volume=145|issue=1-2|pages=91-99|doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2003.11.007|pmid=15065677}} |ref2={{Cite journal|first1=A.M.|last1=Roseman| year=2003|title=Particle finding in electron micrographs using a fast local correlation algorithm. | journal=Ultramicroscopy|volume=94|pages=225–236|issue=3-4|pmid=12524193}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=Signature |website=http://emlab.rose2.brandeis.edu |long description=A particle selection system for molecular electron microscopy. It applies a hierarchical screening procedure to identify molecular particles in EM micrographs. The user interface of the program provides versatile functions to facilitate image data visualization, particle annotation and particle quality inspection. The system design emphasizes both functionality and usability. |version= |contact=niko @brandeis.edu |os support=Linux, Mac OS X, MS Windows |image support=MRC, TIFF |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:GNU General Public License|GPL]] |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=J. Z. |last1=Chen |coauthors=Grigorieff, N. |year=2007 |title=SIGNATURE: A single-particle selection system for molecular electron microscopy |journal=Journal of Structural Biology |volume=157 |issue= |pages=168-173 |pmid= |doi= |pmcid= }} }}
{{EM software tool |name=SwarmPS |website=http://www.imb.uq.edu.au/swarmps |long description=A specialised graphical user interface designed to streamline the process of particle selection from electron micrograph data sets. It provides implementations of both template matching and edge detection algorithms, has an intuitive and easy to use interface, and can be used to obtain useful results on most data sets that are generated in electron microscopy. Currently users can expect to select about 1000-4000 particles per hour of interaction. |version=0.9.2 |contact=d.woolford @imb.uq.edu.au |os support=Linux |image support=Most image formats |cost=Free for academic use under a software license agreement |license= |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=D. |last1=Woolford |coauthors=Ericksson, G., Rothnagel, R., Muller, D., Landsberg, M. J., Pantelic, R. S., McDowall, A., Pailthorpe, B., Young, P. R., Hankamer, B., and Banks, J. |year=2007 |title=SwarmPS: Rapid, semi-automated single particle selection software |journal=Journal of Structural Biology |volume=157 |issue= |pages=174-188 |pmid= |doi= |pmcid= }} }}
{{EM software tool |name=TiltPicker |website=http://ami.scripps.edu/redmine/projects/ami/wiki/TiltPicker |long description=A graphical user interface for picking particles from image tilt pairs for such applications as random conical tilt (RCT) and orthogonal tilt reconstruction (OTR). TiltPicker borrows its interface from Leginon and re-implements many of the tilt picking features of SPIDER WEB that can be run on modern computers. |version=2.0 |contact=vossman77@yahoo.com |os support=Linux, Mac OS X, Windows, other Unices |image support= |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:Apache License|Apache v2.0]] |ref1={{cite journal |author=Voss NR, Yoshioka CK, Radermacher M, Potter CS, Carragher B |title=DoG Picker and TiltPicker: software tools to facilitate particle selection in single particle electron microscopy |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=166 |issue=2 |pages=205–13 |year=2009 |month=May |pmid=19374019 |pmc=2768396 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2009.01.004 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=TMaCS |website=https://sites.google.com/site/rubinsteingroup/particle-selection |long description=Template Matching and Classification System. Template matching identifies candidate particle images while a Support Vector Machine algorithm is interactively trained to distinguish particles from non-particles. |version=1.0 |contact=john.rubinstein@utoronto.ca, jianhua.zhao@utoronto.ca |os support=Linux |image support=MRC |cost=Free/Open Source |license= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Zhao J, Brubaker MA, Rubinstein JL |title=TMaCS: A hybrid template matching and classification system for automated particle selection |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=In Press |issue= |pages= |year=2013 |month= |pmid= |pmc= |doi= |url=}} }} }}
